data.name: StoryText_Builder_Factorum1
data.value: Discarded File: 2.12.2067The first stages of the project have been a massive success. Far beyond what we dared hope for.The thruster and battery are working. Next step is testing the jump drive. I anticipate that taking a while.-Also, let's nip this in the bud."Prototype Technology" is not the final name. I will come up with something much better. It's not like we need something right away. I hear you all snickering. Saying I'm not creative. I am VERY creative. I'll come up with something much better than Prototype Technology - just you watch.

data.name: StoryText_Builder_Factorum2
data.value: INTERCEPTED TRANSMISSION:Dear Representative Colfax,I want to address your frustration with The Cooperative's refusal to ban Prototech. As one of the (many) votes against your proposal, I can offer some insight.It's not that we disagree with the points you raised. You were right to say Prototech can't be trusted. And it is poor policy to rely on the unreliable.However, what is the alternative?To refuse to use technology that The Factorum happily employs? You cannot get the air back in the air-lock, so to speak. This technology is out there.To pretend otherwise, like your proposal in The Cooperative would have us do, is the greater risk. If you want to live by ideals, go join the hippies in Astronauts Without Borders. We have a government to run.

data.name: StoryText_Military_Factorum1
data.value: Discarded File: 1.2.2054Abstract:WhereasThe Second Space Race has witnessed a collapse of our existing social contract;WhereasThe democratization of technology has allowed those who should not have access to the cosmos, access;WhereasWe have routinely seen the best interest of humanity - namely their own protection - sidelined so that upstart profiteers can benefit;WhereasA return to the status quo is not only prudent, it is necessary;Statement:To the members of this committee, it is not a question of if we have the means to restore order. We do. It is a question of if we have the stomach for it.I propose a regular forum to discuss this matter - as well as the construction of a factory where we can begin work on our prototype technology.All in favor?Y: 14All opposed?N: 3The motion passes.

data.name: StoryText_Military_Factorum2
data.value: Discarded File: 21.5.2074AAR for the incident on May 19th, 2074.The Factorum was approached by myself (Hoskel) and three other representatives of the Sol Cooperative.As leader of the group, I presented myself and expressed interest in learning more about them. As the conversation continued, they grew noticeably more hostile. After a few evasive answers, they ceased to respond to my questions.After several more inquiries, I finally got a response.They threatened not only us personally, but the continued existence of the Sol Cooperative.This Factorum mentioned some unknown asset (Prototech), fired upon us (sending Sandoval to the infirmary), and then disappeared.We can safely assume that the GOI jumped away - but the distance they would have needed to travel to not be detected far exceeds what should be possible.Before preparations even begin, we need to know what these people are capable of. We may be well and truly out of our depth.

data.name: StoryText_Military_Factorum3
data.value: INTERCEPTED MESSAGE:Sol Cooperative moves slowly. That is not a problem, that is by design. When we change gradually, that brings stability. But we've got a problem on our hands.Let's say, hypothetically, these "Prototech" blocks turn out to be real. This "Factorum" is not only real, but can somehow produce supertech beyond what we can imagine.Well, we have members of our assembly who are already outspoken critics of Prototech, believing it to be R.O.S. work in disguise.And even if we didn't, we have lengthy procedures that will slow any attempt to improve our arsenals.And even if we didn't, we still have no consistent way of recovering Prototech, meaning planning future upgrades is nearly impossible.So we'll continue under the assumption this threat is a hoax.Otherwise?By the time we adapt, it will be too late for the whole cooperative.

data.name: StoryText_Military_Factorum4
data.value: INTERCEPTED MESSAGE:R.O.S. made a huge mistake. I received one of their messages the other day. Seems they've had a massive leak.What is clear is they don't know what's real or not about The Factorum. They're as in the dark as we are.My assessment? This is an opportunity.First we track The Factorum down. Show them we're useful.Then, we get as much Prototech as we can.And then, we avenge.Independent Terran Workers will not be forgotten.

data.name: StoryText_Military_Factorum5
data.value: INTERCEPTED MESSAGE:"Experts" claim Prototech is too revolutionary. They blame "The Factorum". They claim R.O.S. is a victim.Of course that's what they're saying. WHO PAYS THE EXPERTS? You think this is bad? They've done worse.Sunset Valley.Triton.I.T.W.I have once again submitted my evidence to the Sol Cooperative and NOTHING has been done. How deep does it go?If this Factorum is real - and not just an R.O.S. front - we should be grateful. They're here to liberate us. The best thing we could do, the best thing for HUMANITY, would be to willingly submit. They'll need all the help they can get fighting the R.O.S. demon.Remember our true enemy.

data.name: StoryText_Mining_Factorum1
data.value: INTERCEPTED MESSAGE:On Tuesday Morning, at 07:12 Universal Circadian Time (UCT), we received a distress call from a nearby asteroid - part of the cluster colloquially referred to as "The Pebbles".As I was unable to spot anything from the deck, I ordered a ground crew to approach via jetpack. The crew, upon reaching an unnamed asteroid, reported visuals on two "Prototech Frames" as well as a fully operational "Prototech Battery" and "Prototech Gyroscope". Further investigation revealed no leads to pursue. There were no signs of shipwreck, no hint to who relayed the distress call, and perhaps most distressingly, no presence of The Factorum at all.This, unfortunately, only raises more questions.

data.name: StoryText_Mining_Factorum2
data.value: INTERCEPTED MESSAGE:I've been wondering about the names. "Prototech." "Factorum." What do you think is going on here?Could Prototech be an acronym? I like to think there's some sort of Dr. Prototech out there - maybe the evil leader of The Factorum? Maybe they named the technology after themself?This is worth investigating. I'm getting giddy thinking about it.---It is quite clearly "Prototype Technology." Please do not waste my time with another message like this.

data.name: StoryText_Pirate_Factorum1
data.value: My task was to approach the target and secure resources for Project Prototech (name pending).I tried several approaches.I tried trading, threatening, even begging. Begging, I think, he thought was the funniest.But then it occurred to me. He had the money, the power, the influence, the status, the capital, the technology, the manpower, the momentum, and the popular support.But I was a faster draw to my gun.And I walked away quite happy.Listen people, if we want our organization to prosper, we need to stop playing by their rules. We can have it all, but only if we embrace what our organization can do. I say we ramp up the activity.

data.name: StoryText_Pirate_Factorum2
data.value: NOTICE TO CREW:I love you all, but you don't realize what we've got here. I've given it a few days, chatted with you, hoped you'd realize.Most of you get that Prototech is a game changer. But to you, that means stepping up our amount of raids. Outrunning any lawmen or mercenaries we cross.Think. Bigger.Sol Cooperative can't keep up. And this "Factorum" clearly has other priorities.You're thinking of loot. I'm thinking of Space Stations. Moons. Planets.Prototech is the kind of stuff kingdoms are made from. The kind of stuff that changes maps.

data.name: StoryText_Pirate_Factorum3
data.value: He is Cosmic Lawlessness. A New God.He is King. Leaving A New Gift.PROTOTECH.No rhyme. All reason. Monolith. An altar to worship on. The King of Cosmic Law. A New Gift. The Cosmic King of Lawlessness. A New God.

data.name: StoryText_Pirate_Factorum4
data.value: Message to the Crew:Much as it pains me at times, this ship is a democracy. Well, we've got something to democratize about.I've heard some of you talking about selling the Prototech scraps from that damaged ship.Don't be morons. What kind of pirates would we be if our prey could outrun us? We adapt, or we die.If we don't craft thrusters of our own, we'll be screwed. Think long term. Selling profits us once. Crafting profits us forever.Now, I'm a fair captain, so I'm going to leave it up to a poll. ---Votes for crafting Prototech Thrusters: 1Votes for selling Prototech Components: 23---Addendum:I quit.

data.name: StoryText_Trade_Factorum1
data.value: Discarded File: 9.12.2032The money isn't there anymore. I know I should be happy for what it means for humanity as a whole, but we're a family business. Now that anyone with a little bit of knowledge can put together a rocketship using scrap metal, what good is an installation service?It's okay, we'll adapt.But not everyone can. Some businesses are just too large. I got invited to a meeting with a bunch of "aggrieved businessmen", talking about a way we can oppose modularity. I declined. I see which way the wind is heading. I'll find something new.There's people out there who are angry. And angry people do things that are stupid. Especially when the angry people are the ones with the power to do something about it.

data.name: StoryText_Trade_Factorum2
data.value: Discarded File: 5.20.2074There is a time table. I understand small scale raiding has been employed for the past four years, but this encounter with The Cooperative was unacceptable and sloppy.Not only did our agents fire upon the Sol Cooperative years before we begin to plan our assault in earnest, they were goaded into mentioning Prototech BY NAME.Prototech is not our greatest weapon. Secrecy is. The offending parties are no longer a concern. I have personally ensured they will not be able to jeopardize our secrets again. And I will take the moment to remind all of you to act as befits your station.Your patience will be rewarded properly. So will your impatience.

data.name: StoryText_Trade_Factorum3
data.value: Discarded File: 9.12.2071Karasi, I heard you were talking to IT yesterday about your messages not getting through to me.They got through just fine. I just didn't think there was a point in responding. Candidly, I hoped that you would let it go.Since that doesn't seem to be happening, I'll take a moment to respond.No, I am not concerned. And you shouldn't be either. As a threat analyst, frankly, I'm embarrassed for you.War against modularity? Right that must be wronged? Secret headquarters in deep space?They call themselves THE FACTORUM for clangsake. These people are lunatics. And any use of our resources spent taking them seriously is a waste of time.I expect better from you.

data.name: StoryText_Trade_Factorum4
data.value: INTERCEPTED MESSAGE:You can't make an omelet without breaking a few eggs.And sometimes it is hundreds of eggs. Thousands. In every direction, as far as all can see.Look, I was given a hard job. I was tasked with seeing if I couldn't access recovered Factorum archives. And wouldn't you know it, I succeeded.We've got tons of messages going back decades. Hopefully enough to figure these people out.But...Messages and recordings from our servers - even personal notes - have been sending themselves to seemingly random addresses. Some are even speculating the Factorum server was a honeypot programmed to perform such a task. I apologize for any inconvenience this may have caused you, both professionally and personally. We are working to resolve the issue.

data.name: StoryText_Trade_Factorum5
data.value: INTERCEPTED MESSAGE:Corporate has lost its mind. They want all of this by next quarter. Before you say anything - I know. I tried to explain that no one knows how Prototech works besides the Factorum and I was told we need to "apply" ourselves. Here are the products they want developed. Apparently, this was after a three week (!!!) brainstorming retreat.- Prototech Rifles- Prototech AI (What is that?)- Super Prototech (?)- Prototech 2(Are these not weapons?)- Next-Gen Prototech (???????)- Prototech Neuroblasters (?????????????????)I need you to go to the head office to talk to them. If I go, I might punch someone.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories1
data.value: Been so bored lately that I've been recording my drill when I'm working. It might make a nice backing track for a song.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories2
data.value: I was thinking about why I love my job. It's because every day, when you look at an asteroid, you can see, the progress that you've made.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories3
data.value: Family thinks my cousin, the builder, is the impressive one. Hardly. Without me, where would he be?

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories4
data.value: One second you feel completely alone in space. Then, you feel trapped inside a cave. It gets to you.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories5
data.value: People try so hard to make money. But it's easy. The rocks are just sitting there. Take them and sell them. Works for me.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories6
data.value: If I find a new mineral, I'll be loaded. See the money isn't in the stuff itself - but to sell the naming rights for the new material. I'd be rich.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories7
data.value: That Prototech stuff I've heard about - it's gotta be made of something out here. I just need to keep looking.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories8
data.value: Corporate miners make more - but they just do what they're told. I have my freedom.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories9
data.value: It's all a scam, isn't it? I mine the rock, someone turns it into a drill, then someone sells me the drill, just so I can mine more rock.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories10
data.value: Saw my buddy get caught in a detonation yesterday. I think I need a new career path.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories11
data.value: Asked the boss if he could hook us up with some Prototech. He said no one knows where the stuff comes from. Yeah right. Bet he just doesn't want to pony it up.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories12
data.value: My favorite ore? Iron. It's practically as common as stone. It's always there when you need it.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories13
data.value: I've always had a soft spot for mining Nickel. Maybe people make Medical Components with it. Don't know if it's likely, but it's what I tell myself.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories14
data.value: Silicon might not be the most common ore. Nor the most expensive. But it powers computers. And they keep everything going.

data.name: StoryText_MinerStories15
data.value: Cobalt mining is where it's at. I don't even care what it sells for. It's pretty to look at.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories1
data.value: If I could work with ships all day - and never have to talk with another human being - I think I would finally be happy.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories2
data.value: Reminder: Instead of slow, say the ship is "intended for precise movements." Instead of power-hungry, say it's "built like a workhorse."

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories3
data.value: Some might say anyone can build a ship - and with modular tech, they're right. But man, have I seen some ugly ships in my time.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories4
data.value: I only work inside, helmet off. That acrid smell of welding - that's what it's all about. I won't have it be filtered out.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories5
data.value: Boss got mad at a proposed design. He said it was little more than a box with thrusters on it. It can fly, can't it?

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories6
data.value: I swear, no one appreciates aesthetics anymore. Each time someone brings back a heap of metal that used to be one of my creations, I die a little.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories7
data.value: Forget drills, drives, weapons - forget all of it. What matters to me - and should matter to you - is how fast does your baby soar?

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories8
data.value: The idea that there's machines out there now that make my work obsolete... It's affecting me. I hope this Factorum leaves as quickly as they arrived.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories9
data.value: I see this as my try out. Build a nice enough ship, maybe that new group will recruit me. I'd love some Prototech.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories10
data.value: I've mastered land. I've mastered the air. I've mastered space itself. Now, if only I could find some water…

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories11
data.value: My grandfather insisted he was a better shipbuilder than me - since when he was my age he didn't have access to Grids. I think he's just jealous.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories12
data.value: I know The Factorum's the new kid on the block, but I'm hoping to be recognized by R.O.S. Forget Prototech. R.O.S. is loaded.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories13
data.value: I don't need that Proton-Techno whatever. My ships the best. And I don't care what sort of fancy tech says otherwise.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories14
data.value: I threw out his first ship. Boo-hoo. I honestly thought it was a pile of rubbish.

data.name: StoryText_BuilderStories15
data.value: I'm sick of everything I build needing to have a purpose. Can't a spaceship just exist anymore? Just for the sake of being cool?

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories1
data.value: Raiding isn't all I hoped it would be. Spacesuits are one thing - I prefer shooting flesh.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories2
data.value: I picked up my first gun to fight off raiders. Now look at me. Funny how that happens.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories3
data.value: It's a fine line we walk. Enter space with too many people and we're dead. Too few, there's no one to raid.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories4
data.value: How did I become the leader? Easy. I killed the last one.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories5
data.value: I tried mining. Was no good. I tried building. Back gave out. I tried flying. Destroyed the ship. This is all I got left.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories6
data.value: This is our home. We won't let The Factorum touch it. But to fight them, we're going to need to raid for resources.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories7
data.value: Other raiders come up with excuses. They had no other option, or they started with good intentions. I'm honest - I just like the money.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories8
data.value: I'll hear no more complaints from the crew that we're siphoning some money back to the Cooperative. Why do you think they turn a blind eye?

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories9
data.value: There will be no more attempts to raid The Factorum. We can't afford another loss like that.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories10
data.value: The fake IDs should be here in a week. Then, we'll have the money and no trail to what we've done. Pleasure working with you all.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories11
data.value: Just ran into a ship we'd already hit earlier that month. Crew and I couldn't stop laughing. What are the odds? Anyway, put the poor sap out of his misery.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories12
data.value: I hate that new group. The Factory guys. It's bad news. People are carrying more weapons than ever. I was hoping they'd all be distracted. Easier targets.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories13
data.value: Idea: What if we pretend to be that Factorum group? Maybe we can get people to pay us just through reputation.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories14
data.value: There's a new way we're dividing the pot. Crew gets all the credits we find. In exchange, I get any Prototech.

data.name: StoryText_PirateStories15
data.value: Let's make something clear - there's easier ways to make money. I'm a raider for the sheer love of the sport.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories1
data.value: I sometimes think about who buys our weapons. How many people they've killed. But most of the time, I just think about the money they've spent.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories2
data.value: We're not what we used to be. Weapon sellers used to be the richest people alive. Now? We're just part of the pack.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories3
data.value: Space is dangerous. I sell security. Can't think of something nobler than that.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories4
data.value: Did you hear about those spiders? There's freaking monster spider aliens out there. I can't prove it, but trust me, you'll want a gun.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories5
data.value: Why do I sell weapons? My cousin got killed by pirates. He was just a miner. I'm making sure it doesn't happen again.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories6
data.value: With the weapons I'm selling, I could start my own colony out here. But I don't want a colony. I'm happy here.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories7
data.value: One of my team ran off with a bunch of weapons to start a raider group. Since then, sales have been at an all time high. That isn't right.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories8
data.value: With what we're selling, I'm hoping to attract the new Factorum group. Maybe they'll buy us out?

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories9
data.value: On the one hand, people are scared of The Factorum and need weapons. On the other hand, everyone wants Prototech.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories10
data.value: Trust me, I love peace more than anyone else. And with my guns, you can bring peace just about anywhere.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories11
data.value: I don't know who this new group thinks they are, but this is our home. Whatever isn't bought, I'm using myself to bring them down.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories12
data.value: I started selling weapons in a world I understand. With this Factorum, I'm lost. And potentially, in serious danger.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories13
data.value: See, this Factorum group has their goals all misaligned. If I was them, my first goal would be building a rifle with their supertech.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories14
data.value: I always wanted a conflict - thought I'd be rich. But now that it's here, I can't help but feel like a monster. This has to be stopped.

data.name: StoryText_MilitaryStories15
data.value: I told The Collective - they needed to update their arsenal. Now that The Factorum is here I've got orders coming in, but it's just too late.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories1
data.value: Could we increase our profit margins by sellings guns? Yes. But I won't have something I sold taking a life.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories2
data.value: You buy low, you sell high. You buy where there's plenty, you sell where there isn't. It's not rocket science. Leave that for the engineers.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories3
data.value: Sell at a loss. We can survive it. Our competition can't. Once they're gone, we make it up on the back-end.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories4
data.value: Had a guy open his helmet because he said he couldn't hear me. We were in space. Now he's trying to sue. I'm going to need a Space Lawyer.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories5
data.value: There was a customer who returned an oxygen tank. They said it worked fine then “suddenly stopped.” It was empty. So help me god.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories6
data.value: Some days I look in the great void of space and think if I wasted it all buying and selling. But, well, the cash helps the feeling go away.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories7
data.value: Credits or spacebucks. Call them ClangKoins for all I care. Just spend them here.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories8
data.value: We might not have the cheapest prices. Or the best goods. Or the best security. But you're already here, aren't you? So buy something.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories9
data.value: My boss gave me this journal. Said I'd be a better employee if I start "reflecting on my business sense." I need to get out of here.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories10
data.value: I wish I could be out there mining - but ever since my bum leg, it isn't an option. At least this keeps the credits coming.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories11
data.value: Any luck reaching out to that Factorum? Everyone needs to buy stuff eventually, right?

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories12
data.value: There's no such thing as a price that's "too high". I want Prototech. And you're going to get it for me.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories13
data.value: He told me if I don't make my sales quota, I'll be fired. But no one comes to this sector anymore! I can't work my magic if no one shows up.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories14
data.value: I heard some rumors about an expedition into space. Pushing the frontier. I bet there's money to be made.

data.name: StoryText_TraderStories15
data.value: Independent Terran Workers is trying to get out of what they owe me. They said to take it up with R.O.S. Unbelievable.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories1
data.value: There's no point to the evacuation call. It will be over before they have time to react. Let their last moments be peaceful.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories2
data.value: Put it down in the log - they're looking for a fight. Let's show them why that was a bad idea.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories3
data.value: I told you having a former pirate on the crew was a terrible idea. You need to tell them we are NOT pirate affiliated.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories4
data.value: I guess it's fitting. Live by the salvage, die by the salvage. Whoever is reading this - congratulations on the payday.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories5
data.value: I've gotten out of stickier situations than this. Get the crew together, I'm ready to impress them.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories6
data.value: Just gave up the last way out of here. At least the crew will survive.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories7
data.value: I grew up on Earth. Dying out here... there's worse ways to go.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories8
data.value: If you found these remains, thank you. Thank you for finding me. And remembering me, even for this brief moment.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories9
data.value: I gave him the information two days ago. He should be back by now. He wouldn't have run off. I just need to wait.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories10
data.value: I told the pirates where they can find us. Here's where we make our stand.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories11
data.value: He's not coming back, is he? He said he'd come back for us.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories12
data.value: Let the ship crash. The people are okay - and they're the ones that matter.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories13
data.value: I can't die not knowing what destroyed the ship. Well... I can. And I'm going to. But where did I go wrong?

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories14
data.value: My sister was having her first kid. I was supposed to meet him. I'm not supposed to die here.

data.name: StoryText_DerelictStories15
data.value: I've been in stickier situations than this. Just trust in the plan - and we'll all get out of this alive.
